Cholera - Pakistan (Neelum Valley) 20000720.1193
Cholera - Pakistan (02) 20001002.1700
[1
Date: 5 Jul 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Dawn The Internet Edition 4 July 2001 [edited

Six die of cholera in Mailsi [unconfirmed
------------------------------------------
VEHARI, July 4: More than 100 cholera patients were admitted to government
and private hospitals in Mailsi on Wednesday. According to unconfirmed
reports, at least 6 people have so far died in various private hospitals of
cholera.
A Vehari district health office official said cholera epidemic had broken
out in Faddah Town, where more than 3000 people out of 6000 residents [50
percent were admitted to hospitals during the last 2 days. A doctors' team
with anti-cholera vaccine and other medicines had been sent to Mailsi,
where it has set up a camp.
Some people told this correspondent that the medicines were insufficient in
view of the number of patients, and at least 3 more medical camps should be
set up in the area. They said a large number of patients belonged to poor
families and could not afford to purchase medicines.
According to some people, the epidemic broke out due to mixing of sewage in
clean drinking water from a leaking pipe. They said they had informed the
municipality about it. According to a health official, they had collected a
drinking water sample and sent it to Lahore for laboratory testing.
Meanwhile, the Vehari District Health Officer has advised the people to use
boiled water and avoid over-eating [sic.
--
