******
[2
Date: 5 Jul 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Dawn The Internet Edition 3 Jul 2001 [edited

There are 4 people dead from diarrhea and many others affected in Yamin
Jokhio Goth, 58 km from Karachi and 3 km from Super Highway. The Edhi Trust
attributes the outbreak of diarrhea to the consumption of contaminated
water, food, and the heat.
The exact cause of the deaths could not be established, but medical experts
said these could be the result of cholera, as many of the victims had shown
symptoms of cholera, such as rice water stool. An Edhi team that has set up
its medical camp in the village told visiting newsmen that every second
house in the 50-house village had been suffering from long bouts of
vomiting and diarrhea for the past many days. Dr Liaquat, posted at the
camp, said they had been providing patients with ORS [oral rehydration
salts, an effective treatment and other medicines and were referring
serious cases to Karachi's hospitals.
Residents told newsmen that they got panicked when they found that one
young person had died with the symptoms of vomiting and diarrhea after the
death of a 90-year-old woman. The woman, residents said, had also developed
the same problems before she died. According to a resident, both the deaths
took place in a matter of days, and gradually about 50 residents of the
small village of laborers also began to develop similar symptoms.
According to experts, a number of people, particularly those living in
Kutchi Abadis and on the periphery of Karachi and interior of Sindh, have
contracted cholera resulting in the death of a number of people in the past
weeks. The experts said although there existed no proper documentation
about the number of deaths claimed by the disease in the city, the cholera
positive cases had been reported in various city hospitals, including Aga
Khan University Hospital.
